<?xml version="1.0" ?><entry xml:lang="en" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:planet="http://planet.intertwingly.net/"><id>http://tcsmath.org/?p=2177</id><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/2015/11/18/a-geometric-proof-of-okamura-seymour/" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><title>A geometric proof of Okamura-Seymour</title><summary type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">After using it in the last post on non-positively curved surfaces, I thought it might be nice to give a simple proof of the Okamura-Seymour theorem in the dual setting. This argument arose out of conversations in 2007 with Amit Chakrabarti and former UW undergrad Justin Vincent. I was later informed by Yuri Rabinovich that … <a class="more-link" href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/2015/11/18/a-geometric-proof-of-okamura-seymour/">Continue reading <span class="screen-reader-text">A geometric proof of Okamura-Seymour</span></a></div></summary><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>After using it in the <a href="http://tcsmath.org/2015/11/18/embeddings-and-extendable-geodesics/">last post on non-positively curved surfaces</a>, I thought it might be nice to give a simple proof of the Okamura-Seymour theorem in the dual setting. This argument arose out of conversations in 2007 with Amit Chakrabarti and former UW undergrad Justin Vincent. I was later informed by Yuri Rabinovich that he and Ilan Newman discovered a similar proof.</p>
<p>Note that establishing a <em>node-capacitated</em> version of the Okamura-Seymour theorem was an open question of Chekuri and Kawarabayashi. Resolving it positively is <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1209.2744">somewhat more difficult</a>.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 1</b> <em> <a name="thmos-dual"/> Given a weighted planar graph <img alt="{G = (V,E)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG+%3D+%28V%2CE%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G = (V,E)} "/> and a face <img alt="{F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F} "/> of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/>, there is a non-expansive embedding <img alt="{\varphi:V\rightarrow L_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarphi%3AV%5Crightarrow+L_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\varphi:V\rightarrow L_1} "/> such that <img alt="{\varphi|_F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarphi%7C_F%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\varphi|_F} "/> is an isometry. </em></p></blockquote>
<p>By rational approximation and subdivision of edges, we may assume that <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is unweighted. The following proof is constructive, and provides an explicit sequence of cuts on <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> whose characteristic functions form the coordinates of the embedding <img alt="{\varphi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarphi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\varphi} "/>. Each such cut is obtained by applying the following lemma. Note that for a subset <img alt="{S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S} "/> of vertices, we use the notation <img alt="{G/\partial S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G/\partial S} "/>, for the graph obtained from <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> by contracting the edges across <img alt="{S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S} "/></p>
<blockquote><p><b>Lemma 2 (Face-preserving cut lemma)</b> <em> <a name="lempres-cut"/> Let <img alt="{G = (V,E)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG+%3D+%28V%2CE%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G = (V,E)} "/> be a <img alt="{2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{2} "/>-connected bipartite planar graph and <img alt="{F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F} "/> be the boundary of a face of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/>. There exists a cut <img alt="{S\subseteq V} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%5Csubseteq+V%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S\subseteq V} "/> such that<br/>
</em></p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle \forall\, u,v\in F,~ d_G(u,v) - d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) ~=~ |\mathbf{1}_S(u) - \mathbf{1}_S(v)| \, .  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cforall%5C%2C+u%2Cv%5Cin+F%2C%7E+d_G%28u%2Cv%29+-+d_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%7E%3D%7E+%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29%7C+%5C%2C+.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle \forall\, u,v\in F,~ d_G(u,v) - d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) ~=~ |\mathbf{1}_S(u) - \mathbf{1}_S(v)| \, .  "/></p>
</blockquote>
<p><em>Proof:</em> Fix a plane embedding of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> that makes <img alt="{F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F} "/> the boundary of the outer face. Since <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is <img alt="{2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{2} "/>-connected, <img alt="{F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F} "/> is a cycle, and since <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is bipartite and has no parallel edges, <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(F)\geq 4} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28F%29%5Cgeq+4%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(F)\geq 4} "/>.</p>
<p>Consider an arbitrary pair <img alt="{(a,b)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28a%2Cb%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{(a,b)} "/> of distinct vertices on <img alt="{F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F} "/>. There is a unique path from <img alt="{a} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{a} "/> to <img alt="{b} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{b} "/> that runs along <img alt="{F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F} "/> counterclockwise; call this path <img alt="{\lambda_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\lambda_{ab}} "/>. Consider a path <img alt="{\gamma\in\mathcal P_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma\in\mathcal P_{ab}} "/> and a vertex <img alt="{w\in V} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%5Cin+V%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w\in V} "/>. We say that <img alt="{w} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w} "/> <em>lies below</em> <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> if, in the plane embedding of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/>, <img alt="{w} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w} "/> lies in the closed subset of the plane bounded by <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> and <img alt="{\lambda_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Clambda_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\lambda_{ab}} "/>.</p>
<p>(Note that the direction of <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> is significant in the definition of “lying below,” i.e., belowness with respect to a path in <img alt="{\mathcal P_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_{ab}} "/> is not the same as belowness with respect to the reverse of the same path in <img alt="{\mathcal P_{ba}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bba%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_{ba}} "/>.)</p>
<p>We say that <img alt="{w} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w} "/> <em>lies strictly below</em> <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> if <img alt="{w} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w} "/> lies below <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> and <img alt="{w\notin\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%5Cnotin%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w\notin\gamma} "/>. We use this notion of “lying below” to define a partial order on the paths in <img alt="{\mathcal P_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_{ab}} "/>: for <img alt="{\gamma,\gamma'\in\mathcal P_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%2C%5Cgamma%27%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma,\gamma'\in\mathcal P_{ab}} "/> we say that <img alt="{\gamma'} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%27%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma'} "/> is <em>lower</em> than <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> if every vertex in <img alt="{\gamma'} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%27%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma'} "/> lies below <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/>.</p>
<p>We now fix the pair <img alt="{(a,b)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28a%2Cb%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{(a,b)} "/> and a path <img alt="{\pi\in\mathcal P_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi\in\mathcal P_{ab}} "/> so that the following properties hold:</p>
<ol>
<li><img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\pi) = d_G(a,b) &lt; \mathrm{len}(\lambda_{ab})} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%29+%3D+d_G%28a%2Cb%29+%3C+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Clambda_%7Bab%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\pi) = d_G(a,b) &lt; \mathrm{len}(\lambda_{ab})} "/>.</li>
<li>If <img alt="{a',b'\in\lambda_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%27%2Cb%27%5Cin%5Clambda_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{a',b'\in\lambda_{ab}} "/> are distinct vertices with <img alt="{a'} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%27%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{a'} "/> preceding <img alt="{b'} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%27%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{b'} "/> and <img alt="{d_G(a',b') &lt; \mathrm{len}(\lambda_{a'b'})} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%28a%27%2Cb%27%29+%3C+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Clambda_%7Ba%27b%27%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G(a',b') &lt; \mathrm{len}(\lambda_{a'b'})} "/>, then <img alt="{a' = a} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%27+%3D+a%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{a' = a} "/> and <img alt="{b' = b} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb%27+%3D+b%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{b' = b} "/>.</li>
<li>If <img alt="{\pi'\in\mathcal P_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%27%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi'\in\mathcal P_{ab}} "/> is lower than <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/> and <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\pi') = \mathrm{len}(\pi)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%27%29+%3D+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\pi') = \mathrm{len}(\pi)} "/>, then <img alt="{\pi' = \pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%27+%3D+%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi' = \pi} "/>.</li>
</ol>
<p><a href="https://tcsmath.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/capture.png"><img alt="OKS cut" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-2205" height="277" src="https://tcsmath.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/capture.png?w=300" width="300"/></a></p>
<p>Note that a suitable pair <img alt="{(a,b)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28a%2Cb%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{(a,b)} "/> exists because <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(F)\ge4} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28F%29%5Cge4%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(F)\ge4} "/>. Finally, we define the cut <img alt="{S\subseteq V} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%5Csubseteq+V%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S\subseteq V} "/> as follows: <img alt="{S = \{v\in V:\, v} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS+%3D+%5C%7Bv%5Cin+V%3A%5C%2C+v%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S = \{v\in V:\, v} "/> does not lie strictly below <img alt="{\pi\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi\}} "/>.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Claim 1</b> <em> <a name="clmpres-cut"/> The cut <img alt="{S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S} "/> satisfies the conditions of the lemma. </em></p></blockquote>
<p>For the rest of this section, we fix the pair <img alt="{(a,b)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28a%2Cb%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{(a,b)} "/>, the path <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/> and the cut <img alt="{S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S} "/> as defined in the above proof.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Lemma 1</b> <em> <a name="lemdips"/> Let <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> and <img alt="{y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y} "/> be distinct vertices on <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/> and <img alt="{\beta\in\mathcal P_{xy}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bxy%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\beta\in\mathcal P_{xy}} "/> be such that <img alt="{\emptyset\ne\mathrm{int}(\beta)\subseteq\bar S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cemptyset%5Cne%5Cmathrm%7Bint%7D%28%5Cbeta%29%5Csubseteq%5Cbar+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\emptyset\ne\mathrm{int}(\beta)\subseteq\bar S} "/>. Then <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\beta) - 2 \ge d_G(x,y)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cbeta%29+-+2+%5Cge+d_G%28x%2Cy%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\beta) - 2 \ge d_G(x,y)} "/>. </em></p></blockquote>
<p><em>Proof:</em> If <img alt="{x = y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%3D+y%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x = y} "/> the lemma holds trivially, so assume <img alt="{x \ne y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cne+y%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x \ne y} "/>. Also assume without loss of generality that <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> precedes <img alt="{y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y} "/> in the path <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/>. The conditions on <img alt="{\beta} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\beta} "/> imply that all vertices in <img alt="{\mathrm{int}(\beta)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Bint%7D%28%5Cbeta%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{int}(\beta)} "/> lie strictly below <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/>. Therefore, the path <img alt="{\pi' := \pi[a:x]\circ\beta\circ\pi[y:b]} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%27+%3A%3D+%5Cpi%5Ba%3Ax%5D%5Ccirc%5Cbeta%5Ccirc%5Cpi%5By%3Ab%5D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi' := \pi[a:x]\circ\beta\circ\pi[y:b]} "/> is lower than <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/> and distinct from <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/></p>
<p>By property (3), we have <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\pi') &gt; \mathrm{len}(\pi)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%27%29+%3E+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\pi') &gt; \mathrm{len}(\pi)} "/>, which implies <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\beta) &gt; \mathrm{len}(\pi[x:y])} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cbeta%29+%3E+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%5Bx%3Ay%5D%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\beta) &gt; \mathrm{len}(\pi[x:y])} "/>. Since <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is bipartite, the cycle formed by <img alt="{\beta} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\beta} "/> and <img alt="{\pi[x:y]} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%5Bx%3Ay%5D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi[x:y]} "/> must have even length; therefore, <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\beta) \ge \mathrm{len}(\pi[x:y]) + 2 = d_G(x,y) + 2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cbeta%29+%5Cge+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cpi%5Bx%3Ay%5D%29+%2B+2+%3D+d_G%28x%2Cy%29+%2B+2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\beta) \ge \mathrm{len}(\pi[x:y]) + 2 = d_G(x,y) + 2} "/>. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<blockquote><p><b>Lemma 2</b> <em> <a name="lemshortcut"/> Let <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> and <img alt="{y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y} "/> be distinct vertices on <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/> and <img alt="{\gamma\in\mathcal P_{xy}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Bxy%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma\in\mathcal P_{xy}} "/>. Then <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\gamma) - |\gamma\cap\partial S| \ge d_G(x,y)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%29+-+%7C%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C+%5Cge+d_G%28x%2Cy%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\gamma) - |\gamma\cap\partial S| \ge d_G(x,y)} "/>. </em></p></blockquote>
<p><em>Proof:</em> If <img alt="{\gamma\cap\partial S = \emptyset} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma\cap\partial S = \emptyset} "/> there is nothing to prove. If not, we can write</p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle \gamma ~=~ \alpha_1 \circ \beta_1 \circ \alpha_2 \circ \beta_2 \circ \cdots \circ \alpha_k \circ \beta_k \circ \alpha_{k+1}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cgamma+%7E%3D%7E+%5Calpha_1+%5Ccirc+%5Cbeta_1+%5Ccirc+%5Calpha_2+%5Ccirc+%5Cbeta_2+%5Ccirc+%5Ccdots+%5Ccirc+%5Calpha_k+%5Ccirc+%5Cbeta_k+%5Ccirc+%5Calpha_%7Bk%2B1%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle \gamma ~=~ \alpha_1 \circ \beta_1 \circ \alpha_2 \circ \beta_2 \circ \cdots \circ \alpha_k \circ \beta_k \circ \alpha_{k+1}  "/></p>
<p>for some <img alt="{k\ge1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%5Cge1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{k\ge1} "/> where, for all <img alt="{i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{i} "/>, <img alt="{\alpha_i\subseteq S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha_i%5Csubseteq+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha_i\subseteq S} "/> and <img alt="{\emptyset\ne\mathrm{int}(\beta_i)\subseteq \bar S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cemptyset%5Cne%5Cmathrm%7Bint%7D%28%5Cbeta_i%29%5Csubseteq+%5Cbar+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\emptyset\ne\mathrm{int}(\beta_i)\subseteq \bar S} "/>. Let <img alt="{x_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x_i} "/> and <img alt="{y_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y_i} "/> denote the endpoints of <img alt="{\beta_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\beta_i} "/> with <img alt="{x_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x_i} "/> preceding <img alt="{y_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y_i} "/> in the path <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/>. Further, define <img alt="{y_0 := x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By_0+%3A%3D+x%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y_0 := x} "/> and <img alt="{x_{k+1} := y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_%7Bk%2B1%7D+%3A%3D+y%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x_{k+1} := y} "/>.</p>
<p>By Lemma 1, we have <img alt="{d_G(x_i,y_i) \le \mathrm{len}(\beta_i) - 2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%28x_i%2Cy_i%29+%5Cle+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cbeta_i%29+-+2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G(x_i,y_i) \le \mathrm{len}(\beta_i) - 2} "/> for <img alt="{1\le i\le k} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%5Cle+i%5Cle+k%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{1\le i\le k} "/>. Since <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/> is a shortest path, we have <img alt="{d_G(y_{i-1},x_i) \le \mathrm{len}(\alpha_i)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%28y_%7Bi-1%7D%2Cx_i%29+%5Cle+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Calpha_i%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G(y_{i-1},x_i) \le \mathrm{len}(\alpha_i)} "/> for <img alt="{1\le i\le k+1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%5Cle+i%5Cle+k%2B1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{1\le i\le k+1} "/>. Therefore</p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle d_G(x,y) ~\le~ \sum_{i=1}^k d_G(x_i,y_i) + \sum_{i=1}^{k+1} d_G(y_{i-1},x_i) ~\le~ \sum_{i=1}^k (\mathrm{len}(\beta_i) - 2) + \sum_{i=1}^{k+1} \mathrm{len}(\alpha_i)\,. " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+d_G%28x%2Cy%29+%7E%5Cle%7E+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Ek+d_G%28x_i%2Cy_i%29+%2B+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5E%7Bk%2B1%7D+d_G%28y_%7Bi-1%7D%2Cx_i%29+%7E%5Cle%7E+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Ek+%28%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cbeta_i%29+-+2%29+%2B+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5E%7Bk%2B1%7D+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Calpha_i%29%5C%2C.+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle d_G(x,y) ~\le~ \sum_{i=1}^k d_G(x_i,y_i) + \sum_{i=1}^{k+1} d_G(y_{i-1},x_i) ~\le~ \sum_{i=1}^k (\mathrm{len}(\beta_i) - 2) + \sum_{i=1}^{k+1} \mathrm{len}(\alpha_i)\,. "/></p>
<p>The latter quantity is precisely <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\gamma) - 2k}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%29+-+2k%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\gamma) - 2k}  "/> which completes the proof since <img alt="{|\gamma\cap\partial S| = 2k} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7C%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C+%3D+2k%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{|\gamma\cap\partial S| = 2k} "/>. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<p><em>Proof of Claim 1:</em> Let <img alt="{u,v\in F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu%2Cv%5Cin+F%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u,v\in F} "/> be arbitrary and distinct. It is clear that <img alt="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) \le d_G(u,v) - |\mathbf{1}_S(u) - \mathbf{1}_S(v)|} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%5Cle+d_G%28u%2Cv%29+-+%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29%7C%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) \le d_G(u,v) - |\mathbf{1}_S(u) - \mathbf{1}_S(v)|} "/>, so it suffices to prove the opposite inequality. We begin by observing that</p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) ~=~ \min\left\{ \mathrm{len}(\gamma) - |\gamma\cap\partial S|:\, \gamma\in\mathcal P_{uv}\right\} \, .  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+d_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%7E%3D%7E+%5Cmin%5Cleft%5C%7B+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%29+-+%7C%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C%3A%5C%2C+%5Cgamma%5Cin%5Cmathcal+P_%7Buv%7D%5Cright%5C%7D+%5C%2C+.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) ~=~ \min\left\{ \mathrm{len}(\gamma) - |\gamma\cap\partial S|:\, \gamma\in\mathcal P_{uv}\right\} \, .  "/></p>
<p>Let <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> be a path in <img alt="{\mathcal P_{uv}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_%7Buv%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_{uv}} "/> that achieves the minimum in the above expression. First, suppose <img alt="{\gamma\cap\partial S = \emptyset} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma\cap\partial S = \emptyset} "/>. Then we must have <img alt="{\mathbf{1}_S(u) = \mathbf{1}_S(v)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+%3D+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbf{1}_S(u) = \mathbf{1}_S(v)} "/>. Now, <img alt="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) = \mathrm{len}(\gamma) \ge d_G(u,v)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%3D+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%29+%5Cge+d_G%28u%2Cv%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) = \mathrm{len}(\gamma) \ge d_G(u,v)} "/>, which implies <img alt="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) = d_G(u,v)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%3D+d_G%28u%2Cv%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) = d_G(u,v)} "/> and we are done.</p>
<p>Next, suppose <img alt="{\gamma\cap\partial S \ne \emptyset} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S+%5Cne+%5Cemptyset%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma\cap\partial S \ne \emptyset} "/>. Then, there exists at least one vertex in <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> that lies on <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/>. Let <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> be the first such vertex and <img alt="{y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y} "/> the last (according to the ordering in <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/>) and assume that <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> precedes <img alt="{y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7By%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{y} "/> in the path <img alt="{\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\pi} "/>. Let <img alt="{\hat\gamma := \gamma[x:y]} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat%5Cgamma+%3A%3D+%5Cgamma%5Bx%3Ay%5D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat\gamma := \gamma[x:y]} "/>. Note that <img alt="{\hat\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat\gamma} "/> may be trivial, because we may have <img alt="{x = y} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%3D+y%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x = y} "/>. Now, <img alt="{\gamma\cap\partial S = (\gamma[u:x]\cap\partial S) \cup (\hat\gamma\cap\partial S) \cup (\gamma[y:v]\cap\partial S)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S+%3D+%28%5Cgamma%5Bu%3Ax%5D%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%29+%5Ccup+%28%5Chat%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%29+%5Ccup+%28%5Cgamma%5By%3Av%5D%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma\cap\partial S = (\gamma[u:x]\cap\partial S) \cup (\hat\gamma\cap\partial S) \cup (\gamma[y:v]\cap\partial S)} "/>, whence <a name="eqngamma-hat"/></p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle |\gamma\cap\partial S| ~=~ (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(u)) + |\hat\gamma\cap\partial S| + (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(v)) \, . \ \ \ \ \ (1) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%7C%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C+%7E%3D%7E+%281+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29%29+%2B+%7C%5Chat%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C+%2B+%281+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29%29+%5C%2C+.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle |\gamma\cap\partial S| ~=~ (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(u)) + |\hat\gamma\cap\partial S| + (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(v)) \, . \ \ \ \ \ (1) "/></p>
<p><a name="eqngamma-hat"/></p>
<p> </p>
<p><a name="eqngamma-hat"/></p>
<p>This gives</p>
<p align="center"><img alt="{\displaystyle \begin{array}{rcl} d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) &amp; = &amp; \mathrm{len}(\gamma) - (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(u)) - |\hat\gamma\cap\partial S| - (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(v)) \\ &amp;\geq &amp; \mathrm{len}(\gamma[u:x]) + \mathrm{len}(\hat\gamma) + \mathrm{len}(\gamma[y:v]) + (\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2) - |\hat\gamma\cap\partial S| \nonumber \\ &amp;\geq &amp; \mathrm{len}(\gamma[u:x]) + d_G(x,y) + \mathrm{len}(\gamma[y:v]) + (\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2) \, \ \ \ \ \ (**) \\ &amp;\geq &amp; d_G(u,v) + (\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2) \end{array}}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+d_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%26+%3D+%26+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%29+-+%281+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29%29+-+%7C%5Chat%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C+-+%281+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29%29+%5C%5C+%26%5Cgeq+%26+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%5Bu%3Ax%5D%29+%2B+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Chat%5Cgamma%29+%2B+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%5By%3Av%5D%29+%2B+%28%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+%2B+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29+-+2%29+-+%7C%5Chat%5Cgamma%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S%7C+%5Cnonumber+%5C%5C+%26%5Cgeq+%26+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%5Bu%3Ax%5D%29+%2B+d_G%28x%2Cy%29+%2B+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%5By%3Av%5D%29+%2B+%28%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+%2B+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29+-+2%29+%5C%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%28%2A%2A%29+%5C%5C+%26%5Cgeq+%26+d_G%28u%2Cv%29+%2B+%28%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+%2B+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29+-+2%29+%5Cend%7Barray%7D%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\displaystyle \begin{array}{rcl} d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) &amp; = &amp; \mathrm{len}(\gamma) - (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(u)) - |\hat\gamma\cap\partial S| - (1 - \mathbf{1}_S(v)) \\ &amp;\geq &amp; \mathrm{len}(\gamma[u:x]) + \mathrm{len}(\hat\gamma) + \mathrm{len}(\gamma[y:v]) + (\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2) - |\hat\gamma\cap\partial S| \nonumber \\ &amp;\geq &amp; \mathrm{len}(\gamma[u:x]) + d_G(x,y) + \mathrm{len}(\gamma[y:v]) + (\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2) \, \ \ \ \ \ (**) \\ &amp;\geq &amp; d_G(u,v) + (\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2) \end{array}}  "/></p>
<p>where the first line follows from Eq. <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqngamma-hat">(1)</a> and the definition of <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> and the third line is obtained by applying Lemma 2 to the path <img alt="{\hat\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat\gamma} "/>. If at least one of <img alt="{u,v} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu%2Cv%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u,v} "/> lies in <img alt="{S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S} "/>, then <img alt="{\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2 = -|\mathbf{1}_S(u) - \mathbf{1}_S(v)|} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+%2B+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29+-+2+%3D+-%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29%7C%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbf{1}_S(u) + \mathbf{1}_S(v) - 2 = -|\mathbf{1}_S(u) - \mathbf{1}_S(v)|} "/> and we are done.</p>
<p>Therefore, suppose <img alt="{u,v\in\bar S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu%2Cv%5Cin%5Cbar+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u,v\in\bar S} "/>. Let <img alt="{\beta = \lambda_{ab}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta+%3D+%5Clambda_%7Bab%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\beta = \lambda_{ab}} "/>. For a path <img alt="{\alpha} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha} "/> and vertices <img alt="{w,z} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bw%2Cz%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{w,z} "/> on <img alt="{\alpha} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha} "/>, let us use <img alt="{|wz|_\alpha} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Cwz%7C_%5Calpha%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{|wz|_\alpha} "/> as shorthand for <img alt="{\mathrm{len}(\alpha[w:z])} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Calpha%5Bw%3Az%5D%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{len}(\alpha[w:z])} "/>. By property (1), we have <img alt="{|ab|_\beta &gt; |ab|_\pi} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Cab%7C_%5Cbeta+%3E+%7Cab%7C_%5Cpi%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{|ab|_\beta &gt; |ab|_\pi} "/> and since <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is bipartite, this means <img alt="{|ab|_\beta - |ab|_\pi \ge 2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Cab%7C_%5Cbeta+-+%7Cab%7C_%5Cpi+%5Cge+2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{|ab|_\beta - |ab|_\pi \ge 2} "/>. By property (2), we have <img alt="{d_G(u,b) = |ub|_\beta} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%28u%2Cb%29+%3D+%7Cub%7C_%5Cbeta%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G(u,b) = |ub|_\beta} "/> and <img alt="{d_G(a,v) = |av|_\beta} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%28a%2Cv%29+%3D+%7Cav%7C_%5Cbeta%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G(a,v) = |av|_\beta} "/>. Using these facts, we now derive</p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle \begin{array}{rcl} \mathrm{len}(\gamma[u:x]) + d_G(x,y) + \mathrm{len}(\gamma[y:v]) &amp; = &amp; |ux|_\gamma + |xy|_\pi + |yv|_\gamma \\ &amp; = &amp; |ux|_\gamma + |xb|_\pi + |ay|_\pi + |yv|_\gamma - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp;\ge&amp; d_G(u,b) + d_G(a,v) - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp; = &amp; |ub|_\beta + |av|_\beta - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp; = &amp; |uv|_\beta + |ab|_\beta - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp;\ge&amp; |uv|_\beta + 2 \, . \end{array}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Brcl%7D+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%5Bu%3Ax%5D%29+%2B+d_G%28x%2Cy%29+%2B+%5Cmathrm%7Blen%7D%28%5Cgamma%5By%3Av%5D%29+%26+%3D+%26+%7Cux%7C_%5Cgamma+%2B+%7Cxy%7C_%5Cpi+%2B+%7Cyv%7C_%5Cgamma+%5C%5C+%26+%3D+%26+%7Cux%7C_%5Cgamma+%2B+%7Cxb%7C_%5Cpi+%2B+%7Cay%7C_%5Cpi+%2B+%7Cyv%7C_%5Cgamma+-+%7Cab%7C_%5Cpi+%5C%5C+%26%5Cge%26+d_G%28u%2Cb%29+%2B+d_G%28a%2Cv%29+-+%7Cab%7C_%5Cpi+%5C%5C+%26+%3D+%26+%7Cub%7C_%5Cbeta+%2B+%7Cav%7C_%5Cbeta+-+%7Cab%7C_%5Cpi+%5C%5C+%26+%3D+%26+%7Cuv%7C_%5Cbeta+%2B+%7Cab%7C_%5Cbeta+-+%7Cab%7C_%5Cpi+%5C%5C+%26%5Cge%26+%7Cuv%7C_%5Cbeta+%2B+2+%5C%2C+.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle \begin{array}{rcl} \mathrm{len}(\gamma[u:x]) + d_G(x,y) + \mathrm{len}(\gamma[y:v]) &amp; = &amp; |ux|_\gamma + |xy|_\pi + |yv|_\gamma \\ &amp; = &amp; |ux|_\gamma + |xb|_\pi + |ay|_\pi + |yv|_\gamma - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp;\ge&amp; d_G(u,b) + d_G(a,v) - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp; = &amp; |ub|_\beta + |av|_\beta - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp; = &amp; |uv|_\beta + |ab|_\beta - |ab|_\pi \\ &amp;\ge&amp; |uv|_\beta + 2 \, . \end{array}  "/></p>
<p>Using this in (**) above and noting that <img alt="{\mathbf{1}_S(u) = \mathbf{1}_S(v) = 0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28u%29+%3D+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_S%28v%29+%3D+0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbf{1}_S(u) = \mathbf{1}_S(v) = 0} "/>, we get <img alt="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) \ge |uv|_\beta + 2 - 2 = d_G(u,v)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%5Cge+%7Cuv%7C_%5Cbeta+%2B+2+-+2+%3D+d_G%28u%2Cv%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_{G/\partial S}(u,v) \ge |uv|_\beta + 2 - 2 = d_G(u,v)} "/>. This completes the proof. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<p><em>Proof of Theorem 1:</em> Assume that <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is <img alt="{2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{2} "/>-connected. We may also assume that <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is bipartite. To see why, note that subdividing every edge of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> by introducing one new vertex per edge leaves the metric <img alt="{d_G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G} "/> essentially unchanged except for a scaling factor of <img alt="{2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{2} "/>.</p>
<p>We shall now prove the stronger statement that for every face <img alt="{f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f} "/> of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> there exists a sequence of cuts <img alt="{S_1,S_2,\ldots,S_k} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_1%2CS_2%2C%5Cldots%2CS_k%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S_1,S_2,\ldots,S_k} "/> of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> such that for all <img alt="{u,v} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu%2Cv%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u,v} "/> on <img alt="{f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f} "/>, we have <img alt="{d_G(u,v) = \sum_{i=1}^k |\mathbf{1}_{S_i}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_i}(v)|} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd_G%28u%2Cv%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Ek+%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_i%7D%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_i%7D%28v%29%7C%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d_G(u,v) = \sum_{i=1}^k |\mathbf{1}_{S_i}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_i}(v)|} "/> and that for <img alt="{i\ne j} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%5Cne+j%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{i\ne j} "/>, <img alt="{\partial S_i\cap\partial S_j = \emptyset} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpartial+S_i%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S_j+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\partial S_i\cap\partial S_j = \emptyset} "/>. We prove this by induction on <img alt="{|V|} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7CV%7C%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{|V|} "/>.</p>
<p>The result is trivial in the degenerate case when <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> is a single edge. For any larger <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/> and any cut <img alt="{S\subseteq V} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS%5Csubseteq+V%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S\subseteq V} "/>, the graph <img alt="{G/\partial S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G/\partial S} "/> is either a single edge or is <img alt="{2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{2} "/>-connected. Furthermore, contracting a cut preserves the parities of the lengths of all closed walks; therefore <img alt="{G/\partial S} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G/\partial S} "/> is also bipartite.</p>
<p>Apply the face-preserving cut lemma (Lemma 1) to obtain a cut <img alt="{S_1\subseteq V} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_1%5Csubseteq+V%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S_1\subseteq V} "/>. By the above observations, we can apply the induction hypothesis to <img alt="{G/\partial S_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G/\partial S_1} "/> to obtain cuts <img alt="{\hat S_2,\ldots,\hat S_k} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+S_2%2C%5Cldots%2C%5Chat+S_k%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat S_2,\ldots,\hat S_k} "/> of <img alt="{G/\partial S_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G/\partial S_1} "/> corresponding to the image of <img alt="{f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f} "/> in <img alt="{G/\partial S_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G/\partial S_1} "/>. Each cut <img alt="{\hat S_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+S_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat S_i} "/> induces a cut <img alt="{S_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S_i} "/> of <img alt="{G} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BG%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{G} "/>. Clearly <img alt="{\partial S_1\cap\partial S_i = \emptyset} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cpartial+S_1%5Ccap%5Cpartial+S_i+%3D+%5Cemptyset%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\partial S_1\cap\partial S_i = \emptyset} "/> for any <img alt="{i &gt; 1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi+%3E+1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{i &gt; 1} "/>. Finally, for any <img alt="{u,v\in f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu%2Cv%5Cin+f%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u,v\in f} "/>, we have</p>
<p align="center"><img alt="{\displaystyle d_G(u,v) = d_{G/\partial S_1}(u,v) + |\mathbf{1}_{S_1}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_1}(v)| = \sum_{i=2}^k |\mathbf{1}_{S_i}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_i}(v)| + |\mathbf{1}_{S_1}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_1}(v)|}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cdisplaystyle+d_G%28u%2Cv%29+%3D+d_%7BG%2F%5Cpartial+S_1%7D%28u%2Cv%29+%2B+%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_1%7D%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_1%7D%28v%29%7C+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D2%7D%5Ek+%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_i%7D%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_i%7D%28v%29%7C+%2B+%7C%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_1%7D%28u%29+-+%5Cmathbf%7B1%7D_%7BS_1%7D%28v%29%7C%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\displaystyle d_G(u,v) = d_{G/\partial S_1}(u,v) + |\mathbf{1}_{S_1}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_1}(v)| = \sum_{i=2}^k |\mathbf{1}_{S_i}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_i}(v)| + |\mathbf{1}_{S_1}(u) - \mathbf{1}_{S_1}(v)|}  "/></p>
<p>where the first equality follows from the property of <img alt="{S_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BS_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{S_1} "/> and the second follows from the induction hypothesis. This proves the theorem. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p></div></content><updated planet:format="November 19, 2015 05:31 AM">2015-11-19T05:31:36Z</updated><published planet:format="November 19, 2015 05:31 AM">2015-11-19T05:31:36Z</published><category term="Math"/><category term="Okamura-Seymour"/><category term="Planar embedding conjecture"/><author><name>James</name></author><source><id>https://tcsmath.wordpress.com</id><logo>https://s0.wp.com/i/buttonw-com.png</logo><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/osd.xml" rel="search" type="application/opensearchdescription+xml"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/?pushpress=hub" rel="hub" type="text/html"/><subtitle>some mathematics &amp; computation</subtitle><title>tcs math</title><updated planet:format="February 28, 2020 03:20 AM">2020-02-28T03:20:16Z</updated><planet:module>toc</planet:module><planet:format>atom10</planet:format><planet:http_last_modified>Mon, 21 Oct 2019 08:37:51 GMT</planet:http_last_modified><planet:bozo>false</planet:bozo><planet:items_per_page>40</planet:items_per_page><planet:css-id>james-r-lee</planet:css-id><planet:face>jrl.jpeg</planet:face><planet:name>James R. Lee</planet:name><planet:http_location>https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/</planet:http_location><planet:http_status>301</planet:http_status></source></entry>